ves are in turn inflected by rank, social context andmost crucially, gender. This book examines these sibling relationships, focusing on the important vernacular literatures of Iceland, France, England and Germany, and building on recent research on siblings in psychology, history and social science. Multiple and subtle patterns in sibling interaction are teased out, such as the essential sibling task of "borderwork" (the establishment of individuality despite genetic resemblance), and the tensions caused by the easy substitutability of one sibling for another in certain social situations. When the sibling bond is extended to the in-law relation, complex emotional, strategic and political forces and powerful ambivalences nuancethe relationship still further. Quasi-siblings: foster- or sworn-brothers complete the sibling picture in ways which reflect and contrast with the sibling blood-tie. Carolyne Larrington is a Fellow and Tutor in medieval English literature at St John's College, University of Oxford.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBrothers and sisters in literature. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBrothers and Sisters.  aBrothers.  aEmotions.  aEngland.  aEuropean Literature.  aFamily Dynamics.  aFrance.  aGender.  aGermany.  aIceland.  aIdentity.  aLove.  aMedieval Literature.  aMiddle Ages.  aRivalry.  aSibling Behaviors.  aSibling Bond.  aSibling Emotions.  aSibling Relationship.  aSibling Relationships.  aSibling Stories.  aSisters.  aSocial Context.  aVernacular Literatures.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782045113?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isb